        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This measurement will be made during the closest approach for the best chance to estimate the effect of an interaction with Mars. There will be measurements before, during and after the interaction. The nucleus should be 30 km in size; at 1 AU this is 0.04", so the angular resolution of ALMA is important. Measurements of the HCN line intensties for C/LINEAR, NEAT and Hale-Bopp were on average 1 Jy in a 12" beam. If the flux density is comparable, in our 0.5" beam we would have a 100 to 1 S/N ratio. We need this since the abundance of HCN will depend on an estimate of line optical depth, from the ratio of the hyperfine components. The time on source is 12 minutes, with a calibration time of 16 minutes and overhead of 13 minutes. So shortening the on-soruce time to only a few minutes saves only little time. Thus we have a very good detection of the HCN and perhaps the HNC line and other lines in our 100 MHz band. The continuum S/N should also be excellent, so that we can image the comet. This measurement after the closest approach to Mars will be the best test for an interaction with the planet or its atmosphere.

The USB at 101 and 103 GHz are to measure the dust continuum. 


The time of this measurement can be plus/minus 2 days of the date given.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
