    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The C/Siding Springs will have its closest approach within 120,000 km of Mars on 19 Oct 2014. We plan to measure the comet for scientific and operational
reasons before the time of closest approach (Oct. 14), during the closest approach and after this (Oct. 23). In regard to science, we will determine the mass of
large dust grains, the radial velocities of the molecules, the isotope ratios and the HCN/HNC ratio to better understand the molecular chemistry. With a single
pointing at 3.4 mm, we can measure the content of the nucleus of this comet. We will supplement these results with measurements in the visible, the IR and
shorter mm wavelenths. From these, we will produce an improved model of dust grain size, and from the lines, an extent of the interaction with Mars and the
chemistry of the comet. In addition to the purely scientific goals, our data will be used to enhance estimates of the effects on Mars orbiters.</prp:abstract>
